SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 156
BY SENATOR BARTHELEMY
STUDENTS. Requests the Department of Education to study implementation and
accountability implications of student nonenrollment determinations.
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To urge and request the state Department of Education to study implementation and
3 accountability implications of student nonenrollment determinations.
4 WHEREAS, R.S. 17:10.1 provides for a school accountability system for public
5 schools and school systems and requires the State Board of Elementary and Secondary
6 Education (BESE) to develop and implement a uniform system to measure and report school
7 and school district performance; and
8 WHEREAS, current law requires that public school systems be assigned performance
9 scores based on multiple indicators, including student achievement, academic growth, and
10 graduation rates, and uses those scores to classify schools with a letter grade; that schools
11 are annually evaluated, and those identified as low-performing are subject to interventions
12 and improvement requirements; and
13 WHEREAS, according to the state Department of Education, beginning in the 2025-
14 2026 school year, schools and districts will be measured using a simple, easy-to-understand
15 scorecard built around three expectations for every student: Grow: students should make
16 meaningful academic progress every year; Achieve: students should reach proficiency in key
17 subjects; and Thrive: students should graduate on time and be prepared for college, career,
18 or service; this system replaces an outdated model that had become too complex, difficult
